      "id": "GENUS_REGULUS",
      "name": "Regulus",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Kinglets and firecrests — Europe's and North America's smallest birds, weighing as little as 5 grams yet capable of surviving Scandinavian winters in spruce forest by constant foraging through the night. The goldcrest (kungsfågel — 'king bird') takes its royal name from the brilliant gold and orange crown stripe that is erected into a crest during display and aggressive encounters: the English 'goldcrest' and Latin Regulus ('little king') both reflect this crown. The goldcrest breeds in almost every Swedish spruce forest and migrates in vast numbers each autumn, moving in loose mixed flocks with tits through the coastal zone; in some years hundreds of thousands cross the Swedish coast on a single October day. The firecrest, with its additional white supercilium and blazing orange crown, is slowly expanding northward into southern Sweden as temperatures warm.",
